641
69:01.260 --> 69:05.970
We have M controlled unitary operations that each have cost big O of N squared.

642
69:05.970 --> 69:09.480
So the total cost here
is big O of N cubed.

643
69:09.480 --> 69:14.710
And finally, the quantum Fourier transform has cost big O of n squared.

644
69:14.710 --> 69:17.850
So the total cost is big O of N cubed.

645
69:17.850 --> 69:25.320
In particular, we see that even with our
module exponentiation trick, the cost of the controlled
unitary operations dominates.

646
69:25.320 --> 69:30.300
But nevertheless, the cost
is polynomial in little n.

647
69:30.300 --> 69:37.440
There are also some classical
computations required, like computing the modular exponentiations and running the continued
fraction algorithm,

648
69:37.440 --> 69:47.700
but those computations
also have polynomial cost. And in fact, they can be done in big O of N cubed operations as well.

649
69:47.700 --> 69:54.780
There's only one remaining issue, and that is that we need to get our hands on one of these eigenvectors.

650
69:54.780 --> 69:58.350
How can we do this?

651
69:58.350 --> 70:03.530
The solution is actually very simple. We don't run the circuit
on an eigenvector.

652
70:03.530 --> 70:12.900
We just run it on the state one, meaning the binary
encoding of the number one, which we're thinking
about as an element of ZN.

653
70:12.900 --> 70:16.590
So let's make that
replacement in the diagram.

654
70:16.590 --> 70:20.670
The reason this works is because of this equation right here.

655
70:20.670 --> 70:27.210
The state cat one is in
fact a uniform superposition of the R eigenvectors that
we've been talking about.

656
70:27.210 --> 70:34.350
And that's not immediately obvious, but if you calculate the
sum, you should get cat one.

657
70:34.350 --> 70:41.250
And if we run the circuit on this state, the output that we'll get
will be exactly the same as if we'd randomly chosen J

658
70:41.250 --> 70:45.270
and run the procedure on
the eigenvector psi J.

659
70:45.270 --> 70:50.670
Again, that's not obvious, but an analysis reveals it to be true.

660
70:50.670 --> 70:56.070
And finally, that is it. We have an efficient quantum
algorithm for order finding.

661
70:56.070 --> 71:03.780
There's one very short part
of the lesson remaining and a concerns the relationship between integer factorization
and order finding.

662
71:03.780 --> 71:10.200
I mentioned that if we can solve the order finding problem efficiently, then we can also factor
integers efficiently.

663
71:10.200 --> 71:15.000
And I want to very briefly give you the main idea for how this works.

664
71:15.000 --> 71:21.360
It's completely classical. This part actually has nothing
to do with quantum computing.

665
71:21.360 --> 71:26.220
Here's a method for finding
a non-trivial factor of a given positive integer N.

666
71:26.220 --> 71:33.330
And by the way, this method only works when N is an odd number, and it's not a prime
number raised to a power.

667
71:33.330 --> 71:38.970
Those two cases when N
is even or a prime power can be handled separately.

668
71:38.970 --> 71:45.510
There are efficient classical methods for both detecting and
handling those two cases.

669
71:45.510 --> 71:52.320
This method is probabilistic. It might fail, but the
probability of failure will be at most a half,

670
71:52.320 --> 72:00.060
and we can simply run it
multiple times independently to reduce the probability
of error exponentially fast.

671
72:00.060 --> 72:07.290
First, we choose A between
two and N minus one at random, uniformly.

672
72:07.290 --> 72:10.290
Then we compute the GCD of A and N.

673
72:10.290 --> 72:15.390
And if the GCD happens
to be larger than one, then we've just been incredibly lucky.

674
72:15.390 --> 72:20.340
The GCD will be a factor of N and we can just output it and stop.

675
72:20.340 --> 72:27.900
Otherwise, the algorithm continues on and we now know that A is in ZN star.

676
72:27.900 --> 72:32.820
And now we compute the order of A, which is where we need a quantum computer.

677
72:32.820 --> 72:40.110
Or maybe we have a different
way to compute the order. The algorithm doesn't really
care where it comes from, but the only way that we know
how to do this efficiently

678
72:40.110 --> 72:44.250
is with a quantum computer.

679
72:44.250 --> 72:51.630
If the order of R is even, then we compute the GCD of
A to the power R over two minus one with N.

680
72:51.630 --> 72:59.010
And if that GCD is larger than one, then again we have a factor of N, so we output it and we stop.

681
72:59.010 --> 73:05.280
Otherwise the algorithm has failed. And in that case, we
can go back to the start and choose a different A

682
73:05.280 --> 73:08.880
and hope for a better
outcome the next time around.

683
73:08.880 --> 73:16.050
And that's it. And by the way, once
we found a factor of N, we can recurs on both that factor

684
73:16.050 --> 73:22.290
and divide it by that factor until we have a prime factorization of N.

685
73:22.290 --> 73:25.500
So why should this work?

686
73:25.500 --> 73:32.880
Well, there are two main points. The first is that because A to the power R is congruent to one modular N,

687
73:32.880 --> 73:37.080
we have that N divides A
to the power R minus one.

688
73:37.080 --> 73:44.610
Those two statements
are actually equivalent. This is the definition of mod N that you'll find in number theory books.

689
73:44.610 --> 73:49.590
Second, if R is even, then this equation that
we have here is true.

690
73:49.590 --> 73:53.640
This is the well-known formula
for a difference of squares.

691
73:53.640 --> 73:59.280
In fact, the equation is true for all R, but we need R over two to
be an integer in step four.

